w begins.  The gray ground is much lighter than the shadow, so the shadow shouldnt be so dark. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#aaaaaa><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=vashlestampede>Vash Le Stampede</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(12/7/02 11:22:15 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8077.topic&index=3>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://members.shaw.ca/eraue/ezboard/avatar-vash.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Meeting the sun</span><hr size=1> Yeah the person's shadow doesn't seem that good to me either. Do you have a sujestion for how I can make the guy look more like not a shadow. I think I will fix up the shadows and make them a bit more lighter. <p><!--EZCODE CENTER START--><div style="text-align:center"><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://members.shaw.ca/eraue/ezboard/VashLS1.jpg" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></div><!--EZCODE CENTER END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=killersparrow>Killer Sparrow</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://raider56k.homestead.com/files/angif/fire.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(12/7/02 12:39:24 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm14.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=8077.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://raider56k.homestead.com/files/angif/scorch.gif WIDTH=100 HEIGHT=100></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Meeting the sun</span><hr size=1> -his...her..shadow is too short.<br>
it should be at least...2-3 times (or more) the size it is now.<br>
Especially compared to the stones where the size of the<br>
shadow against the object is +5  : 1<br>
<br>
-if the height of the object is the same as another object.<br>
and placed at the about the same distance from the <br>
lightsource, then both shadows are equal in length.<br>
<br>
-the horizon is...bit messed up....unless the distance between <br>
those objects and the horizon is pretty short. let's say they <br>
were standing on some...hill which brings the &quot;horizon&quot; closer..<br>
Then that is probably possible. But if it isn't then the horizon <br>
will be pretty much.....straight horizontal....if the distance <br>
between horizon and object is reaaaally great, then it may <br>
even turn down at the left and right end.(yes, the earth is a <br>
globe..not a pancake <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> )<br>
<br>
-the person has either his legs cut off or he's just standing <br>
with his legs in the ground/water/mud etc..<br>
If it's the last....to me the &quot;floor&quot; looks like it's made of some<br>
solid substance...or whatever it is..it looks thick..<br>
<br>
-With that bright light the shadow may have fade uniform<br>
or a more..higher contrast. as in the center real black<br>
..sticks. fading to the outer edges. as the surrounding..<br>
light &quot;dissolves&quot; the shadow.<br>
<br>
-to create more depth, you may add a thin light faded outline<br>
to the borders of the figure, mostly on top. or perhaps a few <br>
dark grey shades. Though I doubt you would see much more <br>
than a black silhouette with that amount of light.<br>
<br>
All this are just thoughts. Since I never focused on<br>
lighting and stuff.<br>
